Between February 2019 and November 2020, Spotify spent $1 billion to acquir=
e podcast technology and content, not including exclusive deals with Michel=
le and Barack Obama, Kim Kardashian, DC Comics, and others, the terms of wh=
ich were not disclosed.
Spotify=E2=80=99s strategy here -- backward integration -- is not new in st=
reaming. Netflix is the poster child there. For the first 16 years of its l=
ife, Netflix did deals with studios for non-exclusive rights to their conte=
nt. Then, in 2013, it successfully released its first major original show, =
House of Cards, the rights for which it paid $100 million. That year, Netfl=
ix spent a total of $2.4 billion [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkU2O=
hCAQRk_T7NrwIwgLFrOZaxiU0iatYKBsx9sP3U4yCSkovhQveYwOYU75tFsqSN6lx3MDG-EoCyB=
CJnuB3AdvmeJayNYQb1vPtNQklH7KAKsLi8W8A9n2YQmjw5DiZ4JSLsnDSg-aewbe0KkbO69aOh=
lqqOJUgzJwcd3uA8QRLLwgnykCWewDcSs38XXj33Udx9EUrM_X0oxprVd_bRhLbTraCcrrIQJOS=
_i5v4KHdB9TRIh4H3Y_A9aYBMspZ1QwybhUrWpYY7TjnMLQKckdZUq3g1ETk0IJZzxvby1dZ96U=
fajI8fnGk2xjwiHlEOcaPx9uheUTVA993dc9Bjx7iG5YwF-K8DL9kdbPECHXH_C9w-qXSc0EZa1=
S-lJSHQqhjNBGk0r2qU7Ff-gv3jiURg] on original content. This year, Netflix is=
 expected to spend $19 billion. The more Netflix spends on original content=
, the better its margins get. In 2012, its gross margins were 26.5%. Accord=
ing to Atom Finance [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFUMtuxCAM_JrlGPFec=
uDQS38D8XCyqAlE4LTK35duDpUsW9Z4PJqJHmGt7bJH7Uj-msPrAFvgp2-ACI2cHZrLyTLNjVBy=
JsnKxIwyJHe3NIDd581iO4EcZ9hy9JhreTMo5Yq8LLBFMW4UfQrtpVaahgQ6zCmGGJh63rr-TBl=
KBAvf0K5agGz2hXj0h_h48M9RHus-Lbn4cTVWki2nnFHBxnelpZ7YNBvPOYXw1Ip7yrSRYdYLU0=
ILPycuH5LuK5_6GTr6-DXFupNmS8VQWy7rgL9efoftDQw7bsz9LBkvB8WHDdLtFO_A3t7dCgXaC=
DI5jyMmpgwTlEmtze1sRCGEnoWZDRnKqQ5W-Rf9BbNLgEI], its gross margins are expe=
cted to hit 43.3% this year.=C2=A0
Most people agree that Spotify=E2=80=99s push into podcasts is an attempt t=
o do something similar: the higher proportion of time Spotify listeners spe=
nd on podcasts versus music, the less of its revenue it has to pay labels. =
This is quasi-true for now; while the details aren=E2=80=99t public, podcas=
ts might not impact the amount of money Spotify pays labels under current a=
greements, but more podcast time means more leverage for Spotify in the nex=
t round of negotiations.=C2=A0
Podcasts are big and growing. Spotify isn=E2=80=99t just stealing share fro=
m market-leader Apple in podcasting; it=E2=80=99s stealing from radio and e=
xpanding the podcast ad market. Spotify thinks it can grow podcasting into =
a $15 billion industry. To start, it=E2=80=99s bringing podcasting up to pa=
r with other ad formats through Streaming Ad Insertion, first in its origin=
al & exclusive podcasts, and next, thanks to its Megaphone acquisition, to =
any podcast via the recently announced Spotify Audience Network.=C2=A0
The market clearly understands and appreciates the argument. When I wrote a=
bout Spotify last March, it was trading at $137. A year later, it=E2=80=99s=
 more than doubled to $279.=C2=A0
Source: Atom Finance
Not everyone is convinced, though. In January, Citi put a sell rating on th=
e stock [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkcuOwyAMRb-m7BLxLlmwmM38RsTDS=
dEkEIEzVf5-aLsYyboWsux7dQgOYS31skdpSF4y43WAzfBsGyBCJWeDOqdomeZGKDmRaGVkRhmS=
2rxUgN2lzWI9gRyn31JwmEp-b1DKFXlYWCAuLkiuGcRAGdy9BK14jJGKJfKPrztjghzAwi_Uq2Q=
gm30gHu0mvm78u9fz-RxD9mEMZe9PTjnrjb6EqS7tKJiWqw0-rYMHHEoejhKDa9iG1IalB015HU=
LCNDR3tfGB-0aSfV2iginGlZZ6ZONkHOcU_L2ndJRpI_2kF6aEFm6KXN4k3Vc-ttM3dOHnFYhUm=
wv6UrtDH_883A7be9CpzL3vZ054zZCd3yB-gOGH-xvhvEKG2v8jzg47baYME5RJrc0HUCcqhJ6E=
mQzpzrH0rfxv-geT7pk3], citing no material benefit in app downloads or gross=
 Premium subscriptions from the podcast push.=C2=A0
In my humble opinion, Citi is looking at it the wrong way: the move isn=E2=
=80=99t about short-term download numbers or Premium subscription sales; it=
=E2=80=99s about:=C2=A0
Shifting earshare from nearly 100% label-dependent music to a mix of music =
and podcasting,
Slowly diversifying the revenue mix,=C2=A0
Proving it can build businesses without middlemen,=C2=A0
Building up leverage,=C2=A0
And ultimately, using that leverage to improve margins.=C2=A0
As I wrote last March, Ek has always been focused on winning audio long-ter=
m. He fully expects podcasts to become an increasingly important part of th=
at mix, and is investing accordingly, but music will always be the key. Spo=
tify expects streaming music to be a $75 billion market by 2030, 5x the siz=
e of podcasts. If Spotify is to achieve its 30-40% long-term gross margin t=
arget, it=E2=80=99s going to need to fight the labels on their home turf.=
=C2=A0
Spotify Streams On=C2=A0
Spotify=E2=80=99s stated mission is, =E2=80=9CTo unlock the potential of hu=
man creativity by giving a million creative artists the opportunity to live=
 off their art, and billions of fans the opportunity to enjoy and be inspir=
ed by it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Its externally-unspoken business mission is to build as much leverage over =
the music labels as humanly and algorithmically possible, and one day cut t=
hem out for everything except their back catalogs. It=E2=80=99s finally get=
ting the scale it needs to act.=C2=A0
In 2014, Spotify was a small fry. Pandora led the nascent music streaming m=
arket with a 31% share; Spotify came in fourth at 6%. By 2019, Pandora was =
effectively dead at 2%, and Spotify sat alone atop the leaderboard at 36% m=
arket share, twice Apple Music=E2=80=99s. During its Stream On [https://ema=
il.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE1uxCAMhU8z7BrxH7Jg0U2vgQg4GdQEInBa5fZlJotKBiMs-=
_l9wSOspV72KA3J63J4HWAz_LYNEKGSs0F1KVqmuRFKTiRaGZlRhqTmlgqw-7RZrCeQ45y3FDym=
kt8dlHJFnlbzRYxC94ghjnHiwEfTT6QLGM_DrevPmCAHsPAD9SoZyGafiEd7iM8H_-rxWqqWsg_=
tKJiWawhl798NK_j9o-T-JslyyhkVTDGutNQDG6auwSnMo1bcU6aNnCe9MCW08FPk8iHpvvKhnX=
NDH75fU0m1ueBcasprL38__Q7bu9Atup73Mye8HGQ_bxBv93hDfPNwK2SoHW50Hjs6pgwTlEmtz=
e224xFCT8JMhnTlWHpX_hf9Ax8Vh_o] event, it pegged its own share at 40%.=C2=
=A0
Labels can certainly hurt Spotify by pulling their catalogs, but now, Spoti=
fy can inflict even more damage on labels if it chooses to. For now, it=E2=
=80=99s mutually assured destruction, but it=E2=80=99s becoming less mutual=
, and Spotify=E2=80=99s destruction less assured, by the day.=C2=A0
On the surface, Spotify is a friendly company. Its whole Stream On event wa=
s a celebration of the artists, songwriters, and podcasters who have built =
lives on top of the platform. Ek never came out and said, =E2=80=9CWe need =
you less and less, labels.=E2=80=9D But Spotify is a wolf in sheep=E2=80=99=
s clothing, and if you watch the event closely enough, you=E2=80=99ll see v=
eiled threats everywhere.=C2=A0
Ek opened the event with a speech in which he talked about the state of the=
 industry when Spotify was born (not good) and how streaming saved the day:=
=C2=A0
Over the past decade and a half, what we=E2=80=99ve seen and helped drive i=
s an audio renaissance. And I use that word intentionally. It really is a r=
enaissance, and what it is not is a restoration. We=E2=80=99re moving forwa=
rd, not turning the clock back. People love to look back fondly on the musi=
c industry two decades ago, the era of the record store and the FM radio, a=
 time before piracy. And I understand the nostalgia, I get it=E2=80=A6. But=
 what really strikes me is how limiting it was...
Case in point, back in 2002, just over 30,000 albums were released in the U=
=2ES., and only 8,000 sold more than 1,0=
00 copies, representing 98% of sales =
of new releases. By comparison, in 2020, 1.8 million albums were released o=
n Spotify in the U.S., and six times as many albums represented 98% of the =
streams for these releases. So it's not just the possibility that more arti=
sts can be heard by a global audience, it is that more artists are being he=
ard.=C2=A0
Ek=E2=80=99s opening remarks, and the full event, are worth watching in the=
ir entirety.=C2=A0
Ek spoke softly and almost sweetly, but he sent a message to the labels: =
=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re never going back to the world you dominated. Your po=
wer is waning.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s clear in the numbers: there are 60x mo=
re new albums and 6x as many successful albums today than there were 20 yea=
rs ago. The easier it is to release an album, and the more successful artis=
ts there are, the less power middlemen have.=C2=A0
Over the next 100 minutes, Spotify dropped subtle clues about the labels=E2=
=80=99 diminishing power. Today, Spotify is the unquestioned audio aggregat=
or, which allows it to do all of the things that labels can do, at scale, m=
ore cheaply.=C2=A0
Recall what a label does: A&R Support and Funding, Marketing and Promotion,=
 Distribution, and Admin. Spotify quietly flexed its capabilities in each a=
rea throughout the event (we=E2=80=99re going to ignore Admin - Spotify has=
 dashboards and payments).=C2=A0=C2=A0
