le=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0=
;">Ek opened the event with a speech in which he talked about the state of =
the industry when Spotify was born (not good) and how streaming saved the d=
ay:&nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdfc; margin: 1=
em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>Over the past decade and a half, what=
 we&#8217;ve seen and helped drive is an audio renaissance. And I use that =
word intentionally. It really is a renaissance, and <strong>what it is not =
is a restoration</strong>. We&#8217;re moving forward, not turning the cloc=
k back. People love to look back fondly on the music industry two decades a=
go, the era of the record store and the FM radio, a time before piracy. And=
 I understand the nostalgia, I get it&#8230;. But what really strikes me is=
 how limiting it was...</em></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>Case in poin=
t, back in 2002, just over 30,000 albums were released in the U.S., and <st=
rong>only 8,000 sold more than 1,000 copies, representing 98% of sales of n=
ew releases</strong>. By comparison, in 2020, 1.8 million albums were relea=
sed on Spotify in the U.S., and <strong>six times as many albums represente=
d 98% of the streams for these releases</strong>. So it's not just the poss=
ibility that more artists can be heard by a global audience, it is that mor=
e artists are being heard.&nbsp;</em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1=
a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Ek&#8217;s o=
